= Inspiring Examples
Prior information to exploit: there are only a few active parameters
(*sparse!*), the exact number of which is unknown.


=== Example 1: Compressive Sensing
~~~
{}{img_left}{pic/cs.png}{alt text}{600}{200}{pic/cs.png}
~~~

- In compressive sensing, a sparse signal is simple: it is a parsimonious
sum of the canonical basis vectors  $\{\mathbf{e}_k\}$
- These basis vectors are building blocks for sparse signals.
- The $\ell_1$ norm enforces sparsity w.r.t. the canonical basis vectors.
- The unit $\ell_1$ norm ball is conv$\{\pm\mathbf{e}_k\}$ the convex hull of the basis vectors.
-  A hyperplane will most likely touch the $\ell_1$ norm ball at spiky points,
which correspond to sparse solutions.
- This is the geometrical reason that minimize $\|\mathbf{x}\|_1$ subject to $\mathbf{y} = A\mathbf{x}$
will produce a sparse solution.



=== Example 2: Low Rank Matrix Recovery
~~~
{}{img_left}{pic/mp.png}{alt text}{600}{200}{pic/cs.png}
~~~

- A low rank matrix has a sparse representation in terms of unit-norm,
rank-one matrices.
- The dictionary $D=\{\mathbf{u}\mathbf{v}^T: \|\mathbf{u}\|_2=\|\mathbf{v}\|_2=1\}$    is continuously
parameterized and has infinite number of primitive signals.
- We enforce low-rankness using the nuclear norm:
  \(
  \|X\|_* = \min\{\|\bm{\sigma}\|_1: X=\sum_{i}\sigma_i\mathbf{u}_i\mathbf{v}_i^T\}
  \)
  
- The nuclear norm ball is the convex hull of unit-norm, rank-one matrices.
- A hyperplane touches the nuclear norm ball at low-rank solutions.



=== Example 3: Line Spectral Estimation
~~~
{}{img_left}{pic/line.png}{alt text}{600}{200}{pic/line.png}
~~~
- A line spectral signal is composed of a small number of comlex sinusoids.
- The atoms are  trigonometric moment curves
$
\mathbf{a}(f)=[1~~e^{i2\pi f}~~\cdots~~e^{i(n-1)2\pi f}]^T
$
continuously
parameterized by $f\in[0,1]$
- We enforce spectral sparseness using the atomic norm induced by those trigonometric moment curves $\mathbf{a}(f)$:
  \(
  \|\mathbf{x}\|_{\mathcal{A}} = \inf\{\|\mathbf{c}\|_1: \mathbf{x}=\sum_{i}c_i\mathbf{a}(f_i)\}
  \)
- This atomic norm ball is the convex hull of  trigonometric moment curves $\mathbf{a}(f)$.
- A hyperplane touches the atomic norm ball at sparse line spectral signals.
 
 
 

=== Example 4: Low Rank Tensor Decomposition
~~~
{}{img_left}{pic/tensor.png}{alt text}{600}{200}{pic/tensor.png}
~~~
- A low rank tensor is composed of a small number of unit-norm rank-one tensors
- The atoms are  unit-norm rank-one tensors
$
[\mathbf{u}\otimes\mathbf{v}\otimes\mathbf{w}]_{ijk}:=u_iv_jw_k
$
continuously
parameterized by $\mathbf{u}\in\mathbb{S}^{n-1}, \mathbf{v}\in\mathbb{S}^{n-1}, \mathbf{w}\in\mathbb{S}^{n-1}$.
- We enforce low-rankness using the tensor nuclear norm  induced by those unit-norm rank-one tensors:
  \(
  \|T\|_{*} = \inf\{\|\bm{\lambda}\|_1: T=\sum_{i}\lambda_i\mathbf{u}_i\otimes\mathbf{v}_i\otimes\mathbf{w}_i\}
  \)
- The tensor nuclear norm ball is the convex hull of   unit-norm rank-one tensors.
- A hyperplane touches the tensor nuclear norm ball at low rank tensors. 
 
 
= General Atomic Norm 

=== Definition of Atomic Norm
- Consider a dictionary or set of atoms $\mathcal{A}=\{\bm{\psi}(\nu):\nu\in N\}\subset \mathbb{R}^n$ or $\mathbb{C}^n$.
- The parameter space $N$ can be finite, countably infinite, or continuous.
- The atoms $\{\bm{\psi}(\nu)\}$ are building blocks for signal representation.
- Examples: canonical basis vectors, rank-one matrices, rank-one tensors, trigonometric moment curves, a finite dictionary...
- Prior information: the signal is simple w.r.t. $\mathcal{A}$, i.e., it has a parsimonious
decomposition using atoms in $\mathcal{A}$:
$\mathbf{x}=\sum_{\ell=1}^r c_\ell \bm{\psi}(\nu_\ell)$

- The atomic norm of any $\mathbf{x}$ is defined as (Chandrasekaran, Recht, Parrilo,
& Willsky, 2010)
\(
\|\mathbf{x}\|_{\mathcal{A}}=\inf\{\|\mathbf{c}\|_1: \mathbf{x}=\sum_{\ell=1}^r c_\ell \bm{\psi}(\nu_\ell)\}=\inf\{t>0: \mathbf{x}\in t \text{conv}(\mathcal{A})\}
\)
- The unit ball of the atomic norm is the convex hull of the atomic set $\mathcal{A}$
~~~
{}{img_left}{pic/atom.png}{alt text}{800}{200}{pic/atom.png}
~~~

=== Definition of Dual Atomic Norm
- The dual atomic norm is defined as
\(
\|\mathbf{q}\|_{\mathcal{A}}^*:= \sup_{\mathbf{x}:\|\mathbf{x}\|_{\mathcal{A}}\leq 1} |\langle \mathbf{x},\mathbf{q}\rangle|=\sup_{\mathbf{a}\in\mathbf{A}}\left|\langle \mathbf{a},\mathbf{q}\rangle\right|
\)

- Example: for *line spectral atoms*,  the dual atomic norm is the maximal magnitude of a complex trigonometric polynomial
\(
\|\mathbf{q}\|_{\mathcal{A}}^*=\sup_{\mathbf{a}\in\mathbf{A}}\left|\langle \mathbf{a},\mathbf{q}\rangle\right|=\sup_{\nu\in[0,1]}\left|\sum_{\ell=0}^{n-1}q_\ell e^{j2\pi \ell \nu} \right|
\)

=== View Atomic Norm Minimization as Measure Optimization 
- Rewrite the decomposition $\mathbf{x}=\sum_{\ell=1}^r c_\ell \bm{\psi}(\nu_\ell)$ as
$
\mathbf{x}=\int_{N} \bm{\psi}(\nu) \mu(d\nu)
$

- Here $\mu=\sum_{k=1}^r c_k\delta(\nu-nu_k)$ is a discret signed measure defined on the parameter space $N$.
 
- The atomic norm $\|\mathbf{x}\|_{\mathcal{A}}$ equals the optimal value of an infinite dimensional $\ell_1$ minimization:
\(
\operatorname*{minimize}\limits_{\mu\in\mathcal{M}(N)}\|\mu\|_{TV} \operatorname{\ subject\ to\ }\mathbf{x}=\int_N \bm{\psi}(\nu)\mu(d\nu)
\)

- Here $\mathcal{M}(N)$ is the set of all measures defined on $N$, and $\|\mu\|_{TV}$ is the *total variation norm* of a measure.

- When $\mu=\sum_{k=1}^r c_k\delta(\nu-\nu_k)$ is a discret measure, $\|\mu\|_{TV}=\sum_{k=1}^r  |c_k|=\|\mathbf{c}\|_1$.
 
- When $\mu$ has a density function $\rho(\nu)$, $\|\mu\|_{TV}=\int_N |\rho(\nu)| d\nu=\|\rho(\nu)\|_{L_1}$

- The equivalent measure optimization definition allows us to apply
optimization theory and convex analysis to study atomic norm problems.


= Popular Atomic Norm Problems

- *Atomic decomposition*:
 Given a signal, which decompositions achieve
the atomic norm?

- *Recovery from noise-free linear measurements*: How many measurements
do we need to recover simple signal?

- *Denoising*:
 How well can we denoise a signal by exploiting its simplicity
structure?

- *Support recovery*:
 How well can we approximately recover the active
parameters from noisy data?

- *Resolution limit*:
 What's the fundamental limit in resolving active
parameters?

- *Computational methods*:
How shall we solve atomic norm minimization
problems?





= Atomic Decomposition

Consider a parameterized set of atoms $\mathcal{A}=\{\bm{\psi}(\nu),\nu\in N\}$ and a signal $\mathbf{x}$ with decomposition
$
\mathbf{x}=\sum_{k=1}^r c_k^\star \bm{\psi}(\nu_k^\star)
$
under what conditions on the parameters $\{c_k^\star, \nu_k^\star\}$, we have
$
\|\mathbf{x}\|_{\mathcal{A}}=\|\mathbf{c}^\star\|_1?
$

=== Examples
- For $\mathcal{A}=\{\pm \mathbf{e}_k\}$, this question is trival.
- For $\mathcal{A}=\{\mathbf{u}\mathbf{v}^T:\|\mathbf{u}\|_2=\|\mathbf{v}\|_2=1\}$, the composing atoms should be
orthogonal (Singular Value Decomposition).
- For $\mathcal{A}=\{\pm \mathbf{d}_k\}$, a sufficient condition is that the dictionary matrix $D$
satisfies restricted isometry property.


=== Optimality condition
- Define $\mu^\star=\sum_{k=1}^r c_k^\star \delta(\nu-\nu_k^\star)$. We are asking when $\mu^\star$ is the optimal solution of
\(
\operatorname*{minimize}\limits_{\mu\in\mathcal{M}(N)}\|\mu\|_{TV} \operatorname{\ subject\ to\ }\mathbf{x}=\int_N \bm{\psi}(\nu)\mu(d\nu)
\)
- Atomic decomposition studies the parameter estimation ability of total
variation minimization in the full-data, noise-free case.
- The dual problem:
\(
\operatorname*{maximize} \langle\mathbf{q},\mathbf{x}\rangle \operatorname{\ subject\ to\ } \underbrace{|\langle\mathbf{q},\bm{\psi}(\nu)\rangle|\leq 1, \forall \nu\in N}_{\|\mathbf{q}\|_{\mathcal{A}^*}\leq 1}
\)
- Optimal condition: $\mu^\star$ is optimal if and only if there exists a dual
certificate $\mathbf{q}$ such that
\(
 \begin{array}{ll}
&|\langle\mathbf{q},\bm{\psi}(\nu)\rangle| ~\leq~ 1, \forall \nu\in N\\
&~~~~~~~\mathbf{q},\mathbf{x}\rangle ~=~ \|\mu^\star\|_{TV}
 \end{array}
\)
- Define a function $q(\nu)=\langle\mathbf{q},\bm{\psi}(\nu)\rangle$. The optimal condition becomes
\(
 \begin{array}{ll}
\text{dual~feasibility}:&\|q(\nu)\|_{L_\infty} \leq1 \\
\text{complementary~slackness}:&  q(\nu_k^\star)=\operatorname*{sign}(c_k^\star), k\in[r]
 \end{array}
\)

- To ensure the uniqueness of the optimal solution $\mu^\star$, we strengthen the
optimality condition to:

\(
 \begin{array}{ll}
\text{strict~boundeness}:&\|q(\nu)\|_{L_\infty} <1, \nu\in N/\{\nu_k^\star,k\in[r]\} \\
\text{interpolation}:&  q(\nu_k^\star)=\operatorname*{sign}(c_k^\star), k\in[r]
 \end{array}
\)

