= General Theory

~~~
{}{img_left}{pic/inverse.png}{alt text}{260}{200}{pic/inverse.png}

Atomic norm approach, as a new developing tool, has attracted considerable attention in signal processing, machine learning, and statistics.
Given a set $\mathcal{A}$ of atoms, the atomic norm $\|\cdot\|_{\mathcal{A}}$ is an abstraction of $\ell_1$-type regularization that favors simple models. 
Using the notion of descent cones,
the authors of [http://arxiv.org/abs/1012.0621 "The Convex Geometry of Linear Inverse Problems"] 
 argued that the atomic norm is the *best possible convex proxy* for recovering simple models. 
 The paper [http://arxiv.org/abs/1012.0621 "The Convex Geometry of Linear Inverse Problems"] 
provides a general framework to convert notions of simplicity into convex penaltu functions, 
resulting in convex optimization solution to linear inverse problems.
~~~ 
 

